DcyQzlCVlRXP3RhZz1nZGd0MGMtcC1vLWUzLTIwIiwiY29udGVudFV1aWQiOiJkMTM2NDU4Ni05NGI2LTQwYzQtYmY3OC04OWNkNzYwNDEzZDIifQ&amp;signature=AQAAAU8GidyLaS0sB-ejmwXc0Z0I45rdvRuWwgHKKt5kV9OB&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2Fdp%2FB072C9BVTW">那么 Amazon Basics 的大型保护套</a>是携带整个套件和一堆东西的简单且经济实惠的方式。它可以容纳新的坞站、系统、控制器和您需要的所有布线，舒适整洁。这款豪华保护套甚至有一些时髦的颜色，如霓虹黄或红色，以搭配您的 Joy-Con 或最喜欢的服装。</p><p></p>本文最初发表在 Engadget 上：https://www.engadget.com/best-nintendo-switch-oled-accessories-150048703.html?src=rss]]>; </description><link/><![CDATA[https://www.engadget.com/best-nintendo-switch-oled-accessories-150048703.html?src=rss]]><source_id> engadget_479</source_id><guid ispermalink="false"> d1364586-94b6-40c4-bf78-89cd760413d2</guid><dc:creator>克里斯·诺杜斯</dc:creator><source/><![CDATA[Engadget]]><dc:publisher>恩杰特</dc:publisher><dc:rightsholder>恩杰特</dc:rightsholder><pubDate>Mon, 26 Jun 2023 18:30:11 +0000</pubDate><ingested> 1687831962</ingested><modified> 2023-06-27T02:12:48+00:00 </modified><category><![CDATA[Information Technology]]></category><category><![CDATA[site|engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[provider_name|Engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[region|US]]></category><category><![CDATA[language|en-US]]></category><category><![CDATA[author_name|Kris Naudus]]></category><media:content height="1111" medium="image" url="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2021-12/739828e0-6727-11ec-bb77-871e9834b9b2" width="1760"><media:keywords>标题</media:keywords><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[1]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[ ]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[ ]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[ ]]></media:title></media:content><media:content height="1111" medium="image" url="https://media-mbst-pub-ue1.s3.amazonaws.com/creatr-uploaded-images/2021-12/739828e0-6727-11ec-bb77-871e9834b9b2" width="1760"><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[2]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[Kris Naudus / Engadget]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[A selection of Nintendo Switch OLED accessories gathered against a white background.]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[Nintendo Switch OLED accessories]]></media:title></media:content></item><item><title><![CDATA[Lithium-ion battery creator John Goodenough dies at 100]]></title><description type="html"><![CDATA[<p>技术领域最具影响力的科学家之一去世了。德克萨斯大学奥斯汀分校<a data-i13n="cpos:1;pos:1" href="https://news.utexas.edu/2023/06/26/ut-mourns-lithium-ion-battery-inventor-and-nobel-prize-recipient-john-goodenough/">证实</a>，被广泛认为是锂离子电池发明者的约翰·古迪纳夫 (John Goodenough) 博士去世，享年 100 岁。虽然您可能没有听说过他，但他实际上负责制造手机、笔记本电脑和电动车实用。</p><p>研究人员此前一直在探索锂电池。例如，M. Stanley Whittingham 博士提出了一种将锂与二硫化钛结合起来的设计。然而， <em>《纽约时报》</em> <a data-i13n="elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:The New York Times;elmt:;cpos:2;pos:1" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=c813ae39-7d58-41cb-ac66-ad830606ceef&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=The+New+York+Times&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAeUqLoD0SfKklNM74Dnqqy8xCGs9EyeVZiSAKZkZHssV&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F2023%2F06%2F26%2Fscience%2Fjohn-goodenough-dead.html" class="rapid-with-clickid">指出</a>，古迪纳夫于 1980 年在牛津大学取得了重大突破。他制作了一种具有锂和氧化钴层的阴极，可以产生更强的电压，同时大大提高安全性。它的容量比以前的电池大得多，例如铅酸（用于汽车）和镍镉（用于许多便携式电子产品）。</p><span id="end-legacy-contents"></span><p>直到吉野彰博士放弃原始锂并转而采用更安全的锂离子后，这项技术才得以蓬勃发展。这位科学家为旭化成公司 (Asahi Kasei Corporation) 设计了实用的设计，而索尼 (Sony) 则于 1991 年推出了第一款消费者友好型可充电锂离子电池。您知道接下来发生了什么 — 性能的提高使得移动设备要么更加便携，要么根本就没有变得更便携。之前有一个选项。手机和笔记本电脑可以变得更时尚、更快、更耐用，而电动汽车也终于可行。</p><p>然而，古迪纳夫的责任远不止于此。 20 世纪 50 年代和 1960 年代在麻省理工学院任职期间，他帮助开创了一项技术，该技术最终成为您在许多计算产品中看到的随机存取存储器 (RAM)。他经常与同事分享专利。 90 多岁时，他还是一位活跃的研究人员，直到几年前，他还在开发下一代电池技术，有望为可再生能源和电动汽车带来突破性的性能。</p><p>虽然古迪纳夫在公众圈子里相对不为人知，但他的工作确实得到了认可。他获得了 2019 年诺贝尔化学奖和 2011 年美国国家科学奖章等荣誉。</p><p>各行业正在慢慢摆脱锂离子电池。汽车制造商正在规划配备<a data-i13n="cpos:3;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/nissan-solid-state-battery-ev-release-date-182025167.html">固态电池的电动</a>汽车，以提供更高的密度、更快的充电速度和更低的成本。然而，可以肯定地说，如果没有古迪纳夫的努力，现代科技的格局就不会是现在的样子，而且他的遗产很可能在未来几年内得到体现。</p>本文最初发表在 Engadget 上：https://www.engadget.com/lithium-ion-battery-creator-john-goodenough-dies-at-100-171553322.html?src=rss]]>; </description><link/><![CDATA[https://www.engadget.com/lithium-ion-battery-creator-john-goodenough-dies-at-100-171553322.html?src=rss]]><source_id> engadget_479</source_id><guid ispermalink="false"> e4fd57d0-d0ac-4ff2-9ede-10e332db15d1</guid><dc:creator>乔恩·芬加斯</dc:creator><source/><![CDATA[Engadget]]><dc:publisher>恩杰特</dc:publisher><dc:rightsholder>恩杰特</dc:rightsholder><pubDate>Mon, 26 Jun 2023 17:15:53 +0000</pubDate><ingested> 1687831967</ingested><modified> 2023-06-27T02:12:50+00:00 </modified><category><![CDATA[Technology & Electronics]]></category><category><![CDATA[Handheld & Connected Devices]]></category><category><![CDATA[site|engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[provider_name|Engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[region|US]]></category><category><![CDATA[language|en-US]]></category><category><![CDATA[author_name|Jon Fingas]]></category><media:content height="3385" medium="image" url="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-06/659745f0-143c-11ee-bffc-064463a6ac80" width="5247"><media:keywords>标题</media:keywords><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[1]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[ ]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[ ]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[ ]]></media:title></media:content><media:content height="3385" medium="image" url="https://media-mbst-pub-ue1.s3.amazonaws.com/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-06/659745f0-143c-11ee-bffc-064463a6ac80" width="5247"><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[2]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[Peter Nicholls / reuters]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[John B. Goodenough, 2019 Nobel Prize in Chemistry winner, gestures during a news conference at the Royal Society in London, Britain October 9, 2019. REUTERS/Peter Nicholls]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[NOBEL-PRIZE/CHEMISTRY]]></media:title></media:content></item><item><title><![CDATA[Google Pixel Fold review: The challenger that Samsung needs]]></title><description type="html"><![CDATA[<p>在过去的几年里，三星的 Galaxy Z Fold 系列一直是大型柔性手机无可争议的冠军。但由于缺乏真正的竞争者——尤其是在中国之外——它几乎默认拥有这一头衔。但通过 Pixel Fold，谷歌创造了<a data-i13n="cpos:1;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:YouTube;elmt:;" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=89f68c82-f255-44fa-8db9-03fec996b93a&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=YouTube&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI4OWY2OGM4Mi1mMjU1LTQ0ZmEtOGRiOS0wM2ZlYzk5NmI5M2EiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vd2F0Y2g_dj1nbFRLa2RzMTBNYyIsImNvbnRlbnRVdWlkIjoiN2QyMzI3YzEtNzM5MC00N2M4LTlhZDMtNTAyOWE2MjNhYjc0In0&amp;signature=AQAAAdphrZUJA5lfQEVKNn_GHydYNfSSTSzm5TZvcoyobhUn&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fwatch%3Fv%3DglTKkds10Mc">一个合法的挑战者</a>，其创新设计直接解决了三星在该领域的一些弱点。因此，尽管其 1,799 美元的价格对于大多数人来说是不可能的，但谷歌首款旗舰可折叠手机仍然是一个值得注意的竞争对手。</p><h2>设计与展示</h2><p>Google Pixel Fold 配备 5.8 英寸外部屏幕，打开后可看到灵活的 7.6 英寸内部显示屏，这两个显示屏都是 120Hz OLED 面板。从纸面上看，这听起来与三星在<a data-i13n="cpos:2;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/z-fold-3-long-term-durability-report-heres-what-samsung-still-cant-get-right-130053466.html">Z Fold 4</a>上提供的产品非常相似，但谷歌已经对手机的构造和尺寸进行了研究，以创造出迄今为止该公司设计能力的最佳展示。 </p><span id="end-legacy-contents"></span><div id="58ff9d82291844b4af78b61a0ec165d0"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/nEosoqgXRC4" title="YouTube 视频播放器" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen=""></iframe></div><p><core-commerce id="84758971d298404a9c9ed41b068bdc62" data-type="product-list"></p><p>谷歌没有采用三星那种更薄的指挥棒形状，而是为 Pixel Fold 的 2,092 x 1,080 外部显示屏选择了更宽的 17.4:9 纵横比，从而使设备的形状更像护照。好处是您不需要经常切换到更大的内部屏幕。虽然这看起来只是一个小小的调整，但它却带来了巨大的不同。</p><p> Z Fold 4 的显示屏非常薄，打字时感觉很局促。它实际上只可用于基本的事情，例如查找方向或检查通知。但在 Pixel Fold 上，一切都正常。屏幕足够小，像我这样的手中等大小的人可以轻松到达屏幕的角落，但又足够大，应用程序的外观和行为都可以正常进行。和<em>&nbsp;</em>因为您不需要经常打开设备，所以电池实际上可以使用更长的时间。 </p><figure><img src="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-06/6aac4530-142e-11ee-bfba-a8774cc8bc56" style="height:1200px;width:2000px;" alt="虽然 Pixel Fold 确实存在手机弯成两半的折痕，但谷歌在尽量减少其外观方面做得很好。" data-uuid="7faccd97-2951-37ce-92b5-40e59434f1da"><figcaption></figcaption><div class="photo-credit">摄影：Sam Rutherford/Engadget</div></figure><p>也许更重要的是，谷歌在 Pixel Fold 的铰链和底盘上做了一些漂亮的事情，因此手机的两半之间基本上没有间隙，同时仍然非常薄。它的厚度不到 6 毫米，闭合时厚度约为 12.1 毫米，因此尽管比 Z Fold 4 重一些，但感觉更平衡。除非你的牛仔裤上有油漆，否则将 Pixel Fold 放入口袋中应该不会有太大困难。与许多其他柔性手机不同的是，Pixel Fold 具有 IPX8 防水等级，因此您无需担心意外溅水或浸没。</p><p>外部屏幕更宽的一个副作用是，当您打开 Pixel Fold 时，您会获得非常适合观看视频的横向方向。在外部屏幕上启动剪辑后，您只需展开手机，将其展开即可，无需旋转。谷歌并没有像大多数传统手机那样采用完全无边框的设计，而是为 Pixel Fold 提供了稍大的手柄。这意味着不需要像 Z Fold 4 那样使用低分辨率屏下自拍相机。右上角实际上有空间容纳 8 兆像素相机。铰链周围的额外空间让您可以像平装书一样握住 Pixel Fold，当您将其用作电子阅读器时，这一点尤其令人满意。 </p><figure><img src="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-06/6ab768c1-142e-11ee-99b1-2a112ce4ea60" style="height:1200px;width:2000px;" alt="除了传统的音量摇杆外，Pixel Fold 的电源/锁定按钮中还内置了指纹传感器。" data-uuid="3051c481-6505-3f9a-bf00-642fff90b19d"><figcaption></figcaption><div class="photo-credit">摄影：Sam Rutherford/Engadget</div></figure><p>是时候我要对房间里的大象说话了：是的，有一条折痕。您可以用手指感觉到它，并且根据角度，您也可以看到它。但谷歌已经成功地将其分散注意力的程度降到最低。也就是说，过去三年我一直使用可折叠手机作为我的日常驾驶，所以我可能比大多数人更习惯它。</p><h2>耐用性</h2><p>虽然可折叠手机已经存在了几年，但现在谷歌也加入了这个游戏，潜在的首次购买柔性手机的买家应该注意一些事情。当你第一次打开 Pixel Fold 的盒子时，会出现一条警告，提醒你注意手机的显示屏。谷歌指出，“柔性屏幕比传统手机屏幕更柔软，因此请避免接触沙子、碎屑、指甲或尖锐物体。”此外，谷歌表示，用户不应“移除预装的屏幕保护膜”，并且用户应“避免安装第三方屏幕保护膜”。简而言之，与标准的玻璃和金属手机相比，您必须对可折叠手机更加温和。 </p><figure><img src="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-06/6ab78fd0-142e-11ee-983e-c84f7ca64d50" style="height:1200px;width:2000px;" alt="谷歌表示，Pixel Fold 的铰链是使这款手机既超薄又能够完全折叠的不可或缺的一部分。" data-uuid="c05a6f29-5808-3d64-9155-999d4cfed790"><figcaption></figcaption><div class="photo-credit">摄影：Sam Rutherford/Engadget</div></figure><p>到目前为止，我对 Pixel Fold 的显示屏或其预装的屏幕保护膜没有遇到任何问题。也就是说， <a data-i13n="cpos:3;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/z-fold-3-long-term-durability-report-heres-what-samsung-still-cant-get-right-130053466.html">我拥有三部配备类似屏幕保护膜的 Galaxy Z Fold 手机，</a>这些手机在购买后六到八个月内就出现了气泡，因此随着时间的推移，Pixel Fold 可能会出现类似的问题。当被进一步询问有关耐用性和客户支持的问题时，谷歌发言人告诉 Engadget：“我们已经对屏幕保护膜进行了严格测试，使其能够承受正常磨损。如果您确实遇到问题，可以在<a data-i13n="cpos:4;pos:1" href="https://support.google.com/pixelphone/answer/10227672?hl=en">我们的服务中心</a>付费维修（优先护理客户为 29 美元，超出保修期的客户为 129 美元）。”</p><h2>软件和应用程序</h2><p>在谈论手机的内部显示屏时，我们不能不提及谷歌对应用程序和用户界面所做的一些调整。与 Z Fold 4 类似，谷歌为 Pixel Fold 创建了一个任务栏，只不过这个任务栏稍微短暂一些。在主屏幕上，您可以在底部看到标准的图标行。但是，当您使用应用程序时，您可以向上滑动以查看任务栏，然后从那里拖动图标以在多窗口模式下打开它。 </p><figure><img src="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-06/6aad0880-142e-11ee-a3f7-cd1ededd8d95" style="height:1200px;width:2000px;" alt="当您使用应用程序时，您可以从屏幕底部向上滑动以召唤 Pixel Fold 的任务栏，然后从那里可以非常轻松地选择要显示的第二个应用程序以进行多任务处理。" data-uuid="59b2b913-d92e-3795-bb59-5fba43cff40e"><figcaption></figcaption><div class="photo-credit">摄影：Sam Rutherford/Engadget</div></figure><p>调用任务栏的手势就像向上滑动并按住以查看最近使用的应用程序的较短版本。选择所需的应用程序后，调整窗口大小就像向左或向右拖动分隔线一样简单。如果您希望应用程序切换侧面，可以双击分屏分隔线的中间。这个想法是让任务栏在您需要时出现，并在您不需要时消失。当与 Android 中的应用程序建议功能（图标周围有一个圆环的应用程序）结合使用时，它形成了一种简单但有效的多任务处理方式。</p><p>您还可以使用 Pixel Fold 的双显示屏进行一些操作，例如使用手机的高分辨率后置摄像头进行自拍，或者向拍摄对象实时预览您拍摄照片时的样子。但我们之前已经在 Z Fold 和新的<a data-i13n="cpos:5;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/moto-razr-review-finally-some-real-competition-for-samsungs-flip-foldables-203033514.html">Razr+</a>等设备上看到过这种情况。不幸的是，Pixel Fold 最酷的新功能之一——双屏解释器模式——尚不可用，因为它基于 Android 14 中的功能，而 Android 14 要到秋季的某个时候才会推出。 </p><figure><img src="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-06/6ab768c0-142e-11ee-bdef-808f6727bcf5" style="height:1200px;width:2000px;" alt="YouTube 就是针对可折叠设备进行优化的应用程序的一个例子，当 Pixel Fold 对折时，它会呈现一个特殊的桌面 UI。" data-uuid="fa31c065-276f-3dac-9e1d-9faed3647ea0"><figcaption></figcaption><div class="photo-credit">摄影：Sam Rutherford/Engadget</div></figure><p>谷歌表示，超过 50 个第一方应用程序已经针对 Pixel Fold 等设备的使用进行了优化。 <a data-i13n="cpos:6;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/android-12-l-hands-on-some-big-multitasking-upgrades-but-is-it-enough-180002295.html">我们之前已经体验过</a>一些增强功能，例如 YouTube 中的桌面模式。但有许多精致的示例，包括来自 WhatsApp 等第三方的示例，您只需通过拖放即可共享 Google Photos 中的图像。有了这么多的可用空间，从外部显示切换到内部显示时，您确实会感到充满力量。在玩过<em>《狂野飙车 9》</em>等支持自适应分辨率的游戏后，我真的希望有更多的开发者加入进来。</p><h2>相机</h2><figure><img src="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-06/6aad7db1-142e-11ee-bf5f-a7c7880de96c" style="height:1200px;width:2000px;" alt="得益于更长的 5 倍光学镜头和出色的图像处理能力，与三星 Z Fold 4 相比，Pixel Fold 提供了升级的摄影体验。" data-uuid="796c12d7-8bbc-30c5-a336-40e2c27a2b73"><figcaption></figcaption><div class="photo-credit">摄影：Sam Rutherford/Engadget</div></figure><p>我对 Z Fold 4 最大的不满之一是三星无法提供与 Galaxy S Ultra 相同水平的图像质量。但 Pixel Fold 并没有给人妥协的感觉。它具有 48MP 主传感器、10.8MP 超广角和 10.8MP 长焦（具有 5 倍光学变焦）。将其与谷歌出色的照片处理能力相结合，相机的性能将更加出色。</p><core-slideshow data-slideshowid="986e80f8-28d5-4a7e-8584-e8afae9a6d89"/><p>在白天，Pixel Fold 的照片始终比三星的照片更清晰，同时通常可以提供更多细节以及更好的阴影和高光。即使三星的食物模式被激活，Pixel Fold 也让我的玉米卷晚餐看起来更开胃。在黑暗中拍摄更清晰、曝光更佳的照片方面，谷歌的夜视功能继续占据主导地位。</p><h2>性能和电池寿命</h2><p>为 Pixel Fold 提供动力的是 Google 的 Tensor G2、12GB RAM 和高达 512GB 的存储空间。它的速度并不快，而且正如人们在其他 Pixel 设备上所经历的那样，Fold 有时运行起来有点热。但即使当我同时处理多项任务或试图推动它时，手机也从未感到昏昏欲睡，这就是我真正所要求的。 </p><figure><img src="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-06/6aac6c40-142e-11ee-a5ec-b03bc9a3092a" style="height:1200px;width:2000px;" alt="通过将 Pixel Fold 的铰链移至设备的顶部和底部，谷歌能够打造出一款可折叠手机，在关闭时其两侧之间没有间隙。" data-uuid="ac619add-fabf-3559-85fc-9bdf1f49776a"><figcaption></figcaption><div class="photo-credit">摄影：Sam Rutherford/Engadget</div></figure><p>与此同时，尽管谷歌的 4,820mAh 电池比 Z Fold 4 小一点点，但整体续航时间并没有太大差异，也就是说它相当不错。我在他们的外部和内部显示器上运行了我们的视频概要测试。就前者而言，Pixel Fold 的续航时间超过了三星的大型可折叠手机，其续航时间为 22 小时 21 分钟，而后者的续航时间为 20 分 45 秒。不过，使用更大的屏幕时，Z Fold 4 以 17 分 13 秒的时间领先于 Pixel 的 15 分 42 秒。</p><h2>包起来</h2><p>对于谷歌进入柔性手机领域来说，Pixel Fold 感觉像是一场胜利。其巧妙的铰链和纤薄的底盘使其易于使用和携带，而其更宽的机身兑现了谷歌的承诺，即让手机的外部屏幕更加实用。 Featuring strong water resistance, better cameras and UI tweaks to make multitasking a tiny bit simpler, the Pixel Fold more than holds its own against Samsung&#39;s Z Fold 4. And that&#39;s before considering all the great Pixel-specific features like Call Screener, Recorder and more. </p><figure><img src="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-06/6aad7db0-142e-11ee-8f3b-c64837e67429" style="height:1200px;width:2000px;" alt="On the inside, the Pixel Fold features a 7.6-inch flexible display with a landscape orientation instead of the more portrait-like aspect ratio you get on Samsung&#39;s Galaxy Z Fold line." data-uuid="88e9ad16-58bb-3c0d-abb8-93672cff4607"><figcaption></figcaption><div class="photo-credit"> Photo by Sam Rutherford/Engadget</div></figure><p> My main gripes (you know, aside from its price) are that it occasionally feels like the phone is never fully open. Sometimes I feel like I have to put more pressure on it than I&#39;d like to make it completely flat. And while it would be nice if the Pixel Fold came with stylus support like the Z Fold 4, I&#39;m happy to wait till Samsung, Google or whoever finds room to store a pen inside the device.</p><p> Admittedly, some people may say that the Pixel Fold isn&#39;t really advancing the overall capabilities of flexible phones, as many of its features like dual-window multitasking are already available on devices like the Z Fold 4. The issue is that until we get a critical mass of big foldables, developers aren&#39;t going to consider tweaking or optimizing their apps. That&#39;s why this phone had to come first. With the Pixel Fold, Google brought its style and rhythm to a title fight and didn&#39;t come up short. But, perhaps most importantly, Google now has a device it can use to shape the future of Android beyond typical glass bricks.</p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p> This article originally appeared on Engadget at https://www.engadget.com/google-pixel-fold-review-the-challenger-that-samsung-needs-specs-price-170003458.html?src=rss]]>; </description><link/><![CDATA[https://www.engadget.com/google-pixel-fold-review-the-challenger-that-samsung-needs-specs-price-170003458.html?src=rss]]><source_id> engadget_479</source_id><guid ispermalink="false"> 7d2327c1-7390-47c8-9ad3-5029a623ab74</guid><dc:creator> Sam Rutherford</dc:creator><source/><![CDATA[Engadget]]><dc:publisher> Engadget</dc:publisher><dc:rightsholder> Engadget</dc:rightsholder><pubDate> Mon, 26 Jun 2023 17:00:03 +0000</pubDate><ingested> 1687831978</ingested><modified> 2023-06-27T02:13:03+00:00 </modified><category><![CDATA[Consumer Discretionary]]></category><category><![CDATA[Technology & Electronics]]></category><category><![CDATA[Handheld & Connected Devices]]></category><category><![CDATA[site|engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[provider_name|Engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[region|US]]></category><category><![CDATA[language|en-US]]></category><category><![CDATA[author_name|Sam Rutherford]]></category><media:content height="1200" medium="image" url="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-06/18cbbac0-142e-11ee-bbff-912188388a7a" width="2000"><media:keywords> headline </media:keywords><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[1]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[ ]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[ ]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[ ]]></media:title></media:content><media:content height="1200" medium="image" url="https://media-mbst-pub-ue1.s3.amazonaws.com/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-06/18cbbac0-142e-11ee-bbff-912188388a7a" width="2000"><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[2]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[Photo by Sam Rutherford/Engadget]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[Starting at $1,799, the Pixel Fold is Google's first attempt at making a flagship flexible phone.]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[Pixel Fold review photo]]></media:title></media:content></item><item><title><![CDATA[The best Xbox Series X and Series S accessories in 2023]]></title><description type="html"><![CDATA[<p> It&#39;s been nearly three years since the Microsoft Xbox Series X and S launched, and manufacturers haven&#39;t wasted any time in delivering a plethora of useful Xbox accessories. Want some extra SSD storage? Seagate&#39;s expansion cards are cheaper than ever and easy to install. Need a few extra controllers? You&#39;ve got your pick of choices from Microsoft and third-parties (maybe just throw caution to the wind and splurge for an Elite controller). And it&#39;s always worth getting a wireless headset, both for immersive gaming and chatting with teammates. Here are a few accessories we&#39;d recommend for every Xbox gamer.</p><h2> Controllers: Go stylish, go Pro</h2><p><core-commerce id="fb660a5884514c5d96972fa0d88b9d16" data-type="product-list"></p><p> It&#39;s always smart to have a second controller on hand. Even if you don&#39;t play multiplayer games much, you&#39;ll regret not being prepared for the occasional friend or family member who&#39;s down for a <em>Mortal Kombat</em> match. And at the very least, it&#39;s wise to have a replacement in case something goes wrong with your main controller. (We&#39;ve all smashed our gamepads against the wall for one reason, or another – no judgment.)</p><span id="end-legacy-contents"></span><p> While you could just get <a data-i13n="cpos:1;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Microsoft;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=67071605-d4df-494e-8d9c-c9c236b8bb38&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Microsoft&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI2NzA3MTYwNS1kNGRmLTQ5NGUtOGQ5Yy1jOWMyMzZiOGJiMzgiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubWljcm9zb2Z0LmNvbS9lbi11cy9kL3hib3gtd2lyZWxlc3MtY29udHJvbGxlci84eG41OWNyYnNxZ3o_IiwiY29udGVudFV1aWQiOiI4YTYxNzVmOS1iYjljLTQwNDgtOTExOS1kNGM2ZWI1NGFhMTQifQ&amp;signature=AQAAATv3a0fi7iIV0hRiifqCtqOhmzgucbhAP7SiIJMahMAK&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.microsoft.com%2Fen-us%2Fd%2Fxbox-wireless-controller%2F8xn59crbsqgz%3F">another stock Microsoft controller</a> , there are plenty of options worth considering. The official Xbox <a data-i13n="cpos:2;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI2NmVhNTY3YS1jOTg3LTRjMmUtYTJmZi0wMjkwNGVmZGU2ZWEiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9YYm94LVdpcmVsZXNzLUNvbnRyb2xsZXItQW5uaXZlcnNhcnktU3BlY2lhbC14L2RwL0IwOUdIUVZYM04_dGFnPWdkZ3QwYy1wLW8tZHktMjAiLCJjb250ZW50VXVpZCI6IjhhNjE3NWY5LWJiOWMtNDA0OC05MTE5LWQ0YzZlYjU0YWExNCJ9&amp;signature=AQAAAbJtaDjx9U2WxcuveTnayzxpet0AmjbW0-i6Fulai1An&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FXbox-Wireless-Controller-Anniversary-Special-x%2Fdp%2FB09GHQVX3N">Anniversary Edition gamepad</a> is more expensive, but it has a spiffy translucent design that&#39;ll look great on your coffee table. If you find yourself burning through battery life, consider a rechargeable solution like <a data-i13n="cpos:3;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAebCy5DmRXvW1x0f8KdYUTIf9AvqsIUFmLVIAQeAuIW2&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FPowerA-Dual-Charging-Station-Xbox-x%2Fdp%2FB08J8458GS">PowerA&#39;s dual controller bay</a> . It comes with two AA batteries, and it lets you juice up your gamepads in style.</p><p> For dedicated Xbox gamers, <a data-i13n="cpos:4;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAfH9RFAHDlup4HahzlvHnljKxq_TveN6s253x6X9jd8V&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FElite-2-Controller-Black-Xbox-One%2Fdp%2FB07SFKTLZM">Microsoft&#39;s second-generation Elite gamepad</a> is one of the best controllerrs and could be worth the investment. It has replaceable thumbsticks, rear buttons and a comfortable grip. Not to mention, it&#39;s one of the few Xbox gamepads that you can recharge over USB-C.</p><p> If you&#39;re more interested in playing older games, or are just looking for a different style of controller, we&#39;re also huge fans of <a data-i13n="cpos:5;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI2NmVhNTY3YS1jOTg3LTRjMmUtYTJmZi0wMjkwNGVmZGU2ZWEiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9kcC9CMDhYWThIOUQ1P3RhZz1nZGd0MGMtcC1vLWR5LTIwIiwiY29udGVudFV1aWQiOiI4YTYxNzVmOS1iYjljLTQwNDgtOTExOS1kNGM2ZWI1NGFhMTQifQ&amp;signature=AQAAAQ_zTGagtXKT9a09Z0S7Kpg4xkGyaVbWU48P3TAn4ohK&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2Fdp%2FB08XY8H9D5">8BitDo&#39;s Pro 2</a> . It&#39;s incredibly comfortable, and its directional pad is one of the best on the market. It also makes a great controller for PC gaming (though any recent Xbox controller will also work on computers over Bluetooth).</p> <a class="athena-button rapid-with-clickid" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=shopnow-button&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAATyaZE6kpTG4yf_fMRbXPYxDL2G1C3rJ6j91aLZ5gLm3&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FElite-2-Controller-Black-Xbox-One%2Fdp%2FB07SFKTLZM" id="78fca88108fb420d8722f299bab7ac9c" data-i13n="elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:;sec:shop-now;cpos:1;pos:1">Buy Elite gamepad at Amazon - $180</a> <a class="athena-button rapid-with-clickid" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=shopnow-button&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI2NmVhNTY3YS1jOTg3LTRjMmUtYTJmZi0wMjkwNGVmZGU2ZWEiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9kcC9CMDhYWThIOUQ1P3RhZz1nZGd0MGMtcC1vLWR6LTIwIiwiY29udGVudFV1aWQiOiI4YTYxNzVmOS1iYjljLTQwNDgtOTExOS1kNGM2ZWI1NGFhMTQifQ&amp;signature=AQAAAcal10ne1vxkvC9DfDrapnzSTDBgzVwgM_lICcmZwxZT&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2Fdp%2FB08XY8H9D5" id="d0393efe1166441bb9fc82c133dfdeba" data-i13n="elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:;sec:shop-now;cpos:1;pos:1">Buy 8Bitdo Pro 2 at Amazon - $50</a><h2> Specialized controllers are cool again!</h2><p><core-commerce id="3edd842c738e48e6a73b9a19fd2f58f5" data-type="product-list"></p><p> If you play Microsoft Flight Simulator long enough, you&#39;ll realize you can only go so far with a standard gamepad. Time for a flight stick! After conferring with flying simulator fanatics, and perusing plenty of reviews, we&#39;d recommend jumping on <a data-i13n="cpos:6;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAVZq7udkvgOyemQpdGVPkQdzCUp4xVH8JywxvJtn1XIp&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FThrustmaster-T-Flight-Hotas-One-xbox%2Fdp%2FB07643TW2V">Thrustmaster&#39;s T-Flight Hotas One joystick</a> . It offers realistic five-axis control, 14 buttons and a detachable throttle. And unlike some clunky PC solutions, it&#39;s compact enough to fit on a coffee table or lap desk. (You can also use it with a computer, if you&#39;d like.)</p><p> If you&#39;re more into cars, we were impressed by <a data-i13n="cpos:7;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAROswsx-L4CbIRm6EzHNaQ_UVJy75PooUKZm0Kn9UFDU&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FLogitech-G923-Racing-Wheel-PS4%2Fdp%2FB07PFB72NL">Logitech&#39;s G923 racing wheel</a> . Add it to your gaming setup and it&#39;ll feel like a <a data-i13n="cpos:8;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/logitech-g923-racing-wheel-hands-on-070115330.html">genuine steering wheel</a> , with a comfortable grip, steel paddle shifters, and a trio of solid pedals. Once it&#39;s clamped to a table, it delivers a surprisingly realistic driving experience – all the better to tear through Mexico in Forza Horizon 5. It&#39;s definitely pricey at $400, but it&#39;s high-quality investment that&#39;ll last for many racing games to come.</p> <a class="athena-button rapid-with-clickid" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=shopnow-button&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAbZ_A7wmC1z3mPLaW_UVGlwO5hmh8Ew_Zc5PzeQ7Wy9G&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FLogitech-G923-Racing-Wheel-PS4%2Fdp%2FB07PFB72NL" id="93ed012348734086bcb27f245efe3550" data-i13n="elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:;sec:shop-now;cpos:1;pos:1">Buy Logitech racing wheel at Amazon - $400</a><h2> Bump up your storage</h2><p><core-commerce id="8c90ca7d306d40ad83b5256a75859c18" data-type="product-list"></p><p> If you were lucky enough to nab a new Xbox Series X or S at launch, chances are you&#39;re already familiar with their storage limitations. Luckily, you can easily give yourself a bit more breathing room with one of <a data-i13n="cpos:9;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI2NmVhNTY3YS1jOTg3LTRjMmUtYTJmZi0wMjkwNGVmZGU2ZWEiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9TZWFnYXRlLVN0b3JhZ2UtRXhwYW5zaW9uLVNvbGlkLVN0YXRlL2RwL0IwOEszUzZXSk0_dGFnPWdkZ3QwYy1wLW8tZHktMjAiLCJjb250ZW50VXVpZCI6IjhhNjE3NWY5LWJiOWMtNDA0OC05MTE5LWQ0YzZlYjU0YWExNCJ9&amp;signature=AQAAAQxxbKcgDifcqPMO23L3T4veGdUViqi_H7NkGm56aYRM&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FSeagate-Storage-Expansion-Solid-State%2Fdp%2FB08K3S6WJM">Seagate&#39;s storage expansion cards</a> , which are just as fast as the speedy SSDs inside the consoles. In addition to the 1TB card that arrived at launch, Seagate also recently unveiled 512GB and 2TB options. We&#39;d recommend going for 1TB at this point, but if you can afford it the 2TB SSD will certainly last longer.</p><p> You can also connect traditional, external hard drives, like <a data-i13n="cpos:10;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAdlmswe_1em-sQjCduul8uujJDz6kNGoEBqlh-j6_sFP&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FSeagate-Game-Drive-Green-STEA2000403%2Fdp%2FB01065S79E">Seagate&#39;s 2TB Game Drive</a> , to the Xbox Series X and S over USB. They&#39;re far too slow to run current-gen games at their full speed, but they give you a boatload of storage for a much cheaper price. They&#39;re useful to have around for playing games from the original Xbox, as well as the 360. And they can also be used as &quot;cold storage&quot; to free up space on your precious SSD. Newer games can easily move back and forth between those drives, which prevents you from having to download them again.</p><h2> Tune up your sound</h2><p><core-commerce id="662051baa10a4cbbb7d1089383c44558" data-type="product-list"></p><p> You deserve better than experiencing your video game via crummy TV speakers. While you could just plug in whatever wired headphones you have laying around into your Xbox controller, we&#39;d recommend investing in a wireless gaming headset. They&#39;ll likely sound better, and they remove the whole cord problem entirely. The <a data-i13n="cpos:11;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAUReOyFD2kEaJr9t3EI7Ke_XuJK7EaPUD0p-3KQ18ipX&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FSteelSeries-Arctis-Wireless-Gaming-Headset-Integrated%2Fdp%2FB07RJHH6Q8">SteelSeries Arctis 9X</a> is one of the best Xbox wireless headset options around, with beefy drivers, a comfortable fit and sturdy build quality. We were <a data-i13n="cpos:12;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/2019-04-23-steelseries-arctix-9x-xbox-wireless-headphones.html">impressed during our hands-on testing,</a> as they sounded just as good as the company&#39;s excellent<a data-i13n="cpos:13;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/2018-03-13-steelseries-arctis-pro.html">Arctis Pro PC headphones</a> .</p><h2> Upgrade to a real media remote</h2><p><core-commerce id="20826dfcebd74a43941e240d57b04f0f" data-type="product-list"></p><p> Tired of controlling Netflix playback with your controller? Then pick up <a data-i13n="cpos:14;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAXMg65_XUr9fOYkL6adNo5Aa-h3L7qlVEgxnrA4SJh1P&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2F8Bitdo-Media-Remote-Short-Infrared-x%2Fdp%2FB09B2R2GRM%3Fth%3D1">8BitDo&#39;s Media Remote</a> . Available in long and short designs (the latter removes numbers and other extraneous buttons), they&#39;re well-made remotes that fit the Xbox&#39;s clean aesthetic and, with their low price point, they&#39;re an excellent value. I&#39;ve been using the short model to control 4K Blu-rays and tons of streaming apps, and it&#39;s far easier to use than a controller when it comes to quickly fast-forwarding. Now, I don&#39;t have to put my drink down to skip to another chapter.</p><p></p> This article originally appeared on Engadget at https://www.engadget.com/best-xbox-series-x-series-s-accessories-140035165.html?src=rss]]>; </description><link/><![CDATA[https://www.engadget.com/best-xbox-series-x-series-s-accessories-140035165.html?src=rss]]><source_id> engadget_479</source_id><guid ispermalink="false"> 8a6175f9-bb9c-4048-9119-d4c6eb54aa14</guid><dc:creator> Devindra Hardawar</dc:creator><source/><![CDATA[Engadget]]><dc:publisher> Engadget</dc:publisher><dc:rightsholder> Engadget</dc:rightsholder><pubDate> Mon, 26 Jun 2023 16:25:17 +0000</pubDate><ingested> 1687831954</ingested><modified> 2023-06-27T02:12:43+00:00 </modified><category><![CDATA[Technology & Electronics]]></category><category><![CDATA[site|engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[provider_name|Engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[region|US]]></category><category><![CDATA[language|en-US]]></category><category><![CDATA[author_name|Devindra Hardawar]]></category><media:content height="1281" medium="image" url="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2020-11/830539f0-1f73-11eb-80ff-c43927b926a4" width="2000"><media:keywords> headline </media:keywords><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[1]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[ ]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[ ]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[ ]]></media:title></media:content><media:content height="1281" medium="image" url="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2020-11/830539f0-1f73-11eb-80ff-c43927b926a4" width="2000"><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[2]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[ ]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[ ]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[The best Xbox Series X and Series S accessories in 2023]]></media:title></media:content></item><item><title><![CDATA[Meta’s Quest+ subscription offers two VR titles per month]]></title><description type="html"><![CDATA[<p><ins> <a data-i13n="cpos:1;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/tag/meta/">Meta</a></ins> is getting into the games subscription business. CEO Mark Zuckerberg has announced <a data-i13n="cpos:2;pos:1" href="https://www.meta.com/blog/quest/meta-quest-plus-vr-subscription-service-introductory-offer/">Meta Quest+</a> , a plan that grants users access to &quot;the best titles on the platform&quot; for $8 per month or $60 per year. The subscription is available starting today on Quest 2 and Quest Pro. It&#39;s also coming to<ins> <a data-i13n="cpos:3;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/the-meta-quest-3-is-a-499-mixed-reality-headset-with-full-color-passthrough-141204527.html">Quest 3</a></ins> when that headset arrives this fall. Those who sign up to Meta Quest+ by the end of July will only pay $1 for their first month.</p><p> You&#39;ll get access to two curated titles on the first day of each month. The first two are the hit first-person shooter <em>Pistol Whip</em> and <em>Pixel Ripped 1995.</em> August&#39;s titles are <a data-i13n="cpos:4;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/myst-walkabout-mini-golf-vr-dlc-cyan-inc-mighty-coconut-193541468.html"><em>Walkabout Mini Golf</em></a> <em>&nbsp;</em> and <em>Mothergunship: Forge</em> . As with services like PlayStation Plus Essential, you&#39;ll retain access to the games as long as you remain a member. If you cancel Meta Quest+ and sign up again later, you&#39;ll once again have access to the games from your original membership period. </p><span id="end-legacy-contents"></span><div id="85bd328e423e45feb4bcbae037d67a25"><div style="left:0;width:100%;height:0;position:relative;padding-bottom:56.25%;"><iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/OPvA1gJUAEg?rel=0" style="top:0;left:0;width:100%;height:100%;position:absolute;border:0;" allowfullscreen="" scrolling="no"></iframe></div></div><p> Meta has been embracing subscription models as of late. Along with Meta Quest+, the company this year<ins> <a data-i13n="cpos:5;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/meta-verified-is-a-paid-verification-service-for-facebook-and-instagram-161632996.html">introduced Meta Verified</a></ins> , which is a verification service for Facebook and Instagram. In addition to a checkmark, the subscription includes extra protection against impersonation and &quot;direct access to customer support.&quot;</p><p> This isn&#39;t the only subscription service for a VR headset, however. HTC has offered access to hundreds of VR games, apps and videos through its Viveport Infinity service <a data-i13n="cpos:6;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/2019-01-07-htc-viveport-infinity.html">since 2019</a> .</p> This article originally appeared on Engadget at https://www.engadget.com/metas-quest-subscription-offers-two-vr-titles-per-month-153724017.html?src=rss]]>; </description><link/><![CDATA[https://www.engadget.com/metas-quest-subscription-offers-two-vr-titles-per-month-153724017.html?src=rss]]><source_id> engadget_479</source_id><guid ispermalink="false"> 1089fb08-515e-4a31-b8ab-7a7a2aacbb3f</guid><dc:creator> Kris Holt</dc:creator><source/><![CDATA[Engadget]]><dc:publisher> Engadget</dc:publisher><dc:rightsholder> Engadget</dc:rightsholder><pubDate> Mon, 26 Jun 2023 15:37:24 +0000</pubDate><ingested> 1687831961</ingested><modified> 2023-06-27T02:12:48+00:00 </modified><category><![CDATA[Arts & Entertainment]]></category><category><![CDATA[site|engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[provider_name|Engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[region|US]]></category><category><![CDATA[language|en-US]]></category><category><![CDATA[author_name|Kris Holt]]></category><media:content height="923" medium="image" url="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2022-12/d5ca6d20-81cf-11ed-bfda-10d4831d4be3" width="1600"><media:keywords> headline </media:keywords><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[1]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[ ]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[ ]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[ ]]></media:title></media:content><media:content height="923" medium="image" url="https://media-mbst-pub-ue1.s3.amazonaws.com/creatr-uploaded-images/2022-12/d5ca6d20-81cf-11ed-bfda-10d4831d4be3" width="1600"><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[2]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[Meta]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[The Meta Quest 2 is getting faster thanks to an update]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[The Meta Quest 2 is getting faster thanks to an update]]></media:title></media:content></item><item><title><![CDATA[Urtopia's Chord e-bike is a little overkill for a city ride and that's okay]]></title><description type="html"><![CDATA[<p> Urtopia may be a relatively new name in the e-bike world, but it makes a strong first impression. With its 4G, GPS, mmWave sensors and even light projection turn indicators, the <a data-i13n="cpos:1;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/urtopias-tech-heavy-ebike-shows-that-good-software-is-key-120017530.html">Carbon 1</a> felt like the Inspector Gadget of two-wheeled travel, but its exotic design and road-bike leanings meant it wasn&#39;t for everyone. The company&#39;s second bike, the Chord ($1,799), has a much less divisive aesthetic and – unlike its sibling – practicalities like gears and a more upright (and city-friendly) ride. Importantly, the Chord contains all the wireless connectivity of the Carbon 1 at a cheaper price, possibly making it a more compelling package overall.</p><p> The Chord feels like Urtopia&#39;s attempt at a stylish city bike in the vague style of <a data-i13n="cpos:2;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/cowboy-4-ebike-adaptive-power-update-test-ride-134503675.html">Cowboy</a> or <a data-i13n="cpos:3;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/vanmoof-ebike-s5-a5-test-ride-pricing-150525845.html">VanMoof</a> . The Chord is apparently inspired by pianos, with its black and white colorway and the melodic notes that play when you cycle through the power modes. At 46 pounds (21 kilograms), it&#39;s noticeably heavier than the Carbon 1 (33 pounds/15 kg), but it&#39;s on par with other models in the same category.</p><span id="end-legacy-contents"></span><p> The motor is a pretty straightforward 350W hub powered by a removable 360Wh battery. Top assisted speed is 20MPH over four modes: Eco, Comfort, Sport and Turbo. The maximum range is an estimated 75 miles, but that will obviously depend on how much assistance you use. As a Class 1 ebike, there&#39;s no throttle mode here; instead, there&#39;s a Turbo mode with barely any need to pedal to get you up to that maximum speed. As mentioned, the Chord comes with an 8-speed Shimano gear system which, combined with the assistance modes, make for a flexible ride in terms of speed and effort. </p><figure><img src="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-06/7e555340-09d1-11ee-bfff-b7f3441dba54" style="height:1237px;width:2000px;" alt="Urtopia&#39;s Chord e-bike pictured on a sunny promenade." data-uuid="6183c4a9-58db-3656-8e58-bcf918b1f464"><figcaption></figcaption><div class="photo-credit"> Photo by James Trew / Engadget</div></figure><p> The more interesting features with Urtopia bikes come from its connectivity: WiFi, Bluetooth, GPS and 4G. Combined with an accelerometer and a gyroscope the Chord has a surprising amount of situational awareness, which I&#39;ll get to later. Oh, you can also speak to the bike to change settings and use it as a Bluetooth speaker as you ride while receiving visual directions on the dot-matrix screen contained in the “smart box” bike computer. Did I mention there&#39;s a comprehensive app with ride tracking, navigation and deeper settings, too?</p><p> Taking the Chord out for the first time, it was hard to ignore the extra weight compared to the aforementioned Carbon 1, but also the similarly pitched <a data-i13n="cpos:4;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/tenways-cgo600-preview-143051234.html">Tenways</a> . It&#39;s not chonky in the same way something like the 63-pound (28-kilogram) <a data-i13n="elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:;elmt:;cpos:5;pos:1" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsImxhbmRpbmdVcmwiOiJodHRwczovL3d3dy52ZWxvdHJpY2Jpa2UuY29tL3Byb2R1Y3RzL3ZlbG90cmljLWRpc2NvdmVyLTE_dmFyaWFudD00MTA0NTY0ODMxMDQ1NSIsImNvbnRlbnRVdWlkIjoiNzY5OTJkYzgtN2FlZi00NmI1LTlmNDgtOGNjMDE3OWRkNjExIn0&amp;signature=AQAAAetOjBA8VaJZjkKSW_ScIrCk5GpdQp3tiPRuEEGJ3QqN&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.velotricbike.com%2Fproducts%2Fvelotric-discover-1%3Fvariant%3D41045648310455" class="rapid-with-clickid">Velotric Discover 1</a> is but those extra pounds were noticeable the first time I tried hustling it (upright) into the elevator in my apartment block. Thankfully, it&#39;s not something you&#39;ll notice so much while pedaling.</p><p> The riding position is naturally more upright and it makes for a comfortable cruise around town. It&#39;s not designed for off-road, but if you find yourself on uneven pavement or even a short stint on a dirt trail it does a decent job considering. The motor uses a torque sensor to decide when to kick in; it&#39;s a very common system right now and does a good job of delivering power just as you need it.</p><p> Now, about that power. In the scheme of things, a 350W motor is a pretty standard entry-level option; it&#39;s not about to pull your wrists out of their sockets when it kicks in, but it&#39;s gets you to that 20MPH max speed in good time, as long as you&#39;re willing to do the your part on the pedals. The three power modes are spaced adequately for whether you just want a little help or just wanna surprise that weekend warrior as you pass them barely pedaling. Turbo mode will reach max power without you really trying too hard – it&#39;s a good option for if you&#39;re feeling really pooped, and it doesn&#39;t feel like the bike is pulling away from you, which can sometimes be the case with similar modes on higher-powered bikes. </p><figure><img src="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-06/75478e70-09d2-11ee-bf9a-aa796e11a7ee" style="height:1333px;width:2000px;" alt="Urtopia e-bike&#39;s ride computer." data-uuid="85a74e5e-7a12-360b-8aa2-7891991ecff6"><figcaption></figcaption><div class="photo-credit"> Photo by James Trew / Engadget</div></figure><p> Utopia&#39;s heavy-tech approach made the Carbon 1 stand out, but it also felt a little unpolished, at least in the first iteration of the app. The built-in GPS and 4G are meant to automatically record your rides and serve them up in the app with a map and statistics. Initially this felt a bit hit-and-miss. The fingerprint reader in the Carbon 1 was a nice touch, too, and it even doubled as an electric bell, but unfortunately it would often sound about half a second after I needed it. With the newer Chord, the software feels more finished from the get-go.</p><p> For starters, the bell is still digital (you can even change the sound), but it&#39;s triggered by a much clickier button that&#39;s much more responsive. More importantly, the app feels more refined now and I haven&#39;t seen any rides go missing during my time with it. In fact, they appear almost instantly once I finish.</p><p> Of course, automatically mapping rides is cool, but it&#39;s not the primary purpose of the 4G/GPS. <em>That</em> would be the ability to track your bike if someone steals it. As long as the Chord&#39;s within cell coverage, you&#39;ll be able to see its last known location via the app. You can also set it so you receive notification the moment the bike moves – potentially giving you a heads up before a thief can ride off with it. Of course, if the battery runs out or the GPS can&#39;t see the sky it won&#39;t update the app, but the cell lasts for a good amount of time in standby and it only fully turns off if you remove the battery, which requires a key (or bike-breaking brute force).</p><p> A quick note on the battery: Its placement under the top tube is a cunning way to semi-hide it, but also provides a little more protection from the elements. On the flip side, there&#39;s no way to fully turn the bike off, so the 4G connection will gently drain the power between rides unless you remove it. In my testing, I also found that the estimated max range of 75 miles feels a little optimistic. It might be possible under optimal conditions, but even on shorter rides of 11 miles, with mixed use of modes and terrain, I had used up a claimed 25 percent of the cell. So if very long rides are your thing, take note.</p><p> If, upon hearing about all this 4G data you&#39;ll be using, your first question was how much that&#39;ll cost, the answer is nothing for the first year and then $29 annually after that. While it feels like everything has a subscription attached to it these days, this feels reasonable for the functionality you get out of it – especially if your bike <em>does</em> go missing and this helps you find it.</p><p> Beyond knowing where the bike is, the Chord can also guide you to your destination via built-in navigation. To be clear, it&#39;s handled by the app, but when your phone is connected to the bike, the directions will appear on the dot-matrix style display. This also means you can keep your handset safely in your pocket or bag – unlike some bikes that make your phone the bike&#39;s computer, forcing it to remain exposed to the elements. </p><figure><img src="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-06/b0636470-09d2-11ee-bbdb-2e1a020b1988" style="height:1333px;width:2000px;" alt="Urtopia&#39;s Chord e-bike pictured in front of Valencia&#39;s Arts and Sciences." data-uuid="af8b066c-7835-35e6-8463-0b51bf1fb642"><figcaption></figcaption><div class="photo-credit"> Photo by James Trew / Engadget</div></figure><p> With the Carbon 1, I thought the option to play music through the built-in speaker was a novelty at best. The Chord hasn&#39;t changed my mind either. Your music is going to sound pretty bad, but it&#39;s a fun party trick nonetheless. Perhaps it&#39;s more useful for podcasts and audiobooks? Just know that it&#39;s something you <em>can</em> do (but not necessarily something you should). The voice control is a little more practical, but I rarely find a moment where I&#39;d rather lean into the bike and talk to it instead of using the app&#39;s controls.</p><p> Another interesting change from the Carbon 1 is that the smart box (formerly, smartbar) is no longer built into the bike. On the Chord it&#39;s a separate unit that you attach manually, opening the door for some level of modularity. Urtopia hints at this in its press materials, suggesting that in the future you could upgrade to a different smart box with a better display, or new features which is an interesting concept if nothing else.</p><p> With just its second bike, Urtopia is showing a promising mix of consistency and growth (where needed). The Chord is a pretty enough bike that, if it&#39;s to your taste, would serve as a good general purpose city e-bike. It&#39;s not the most powerful, nor the most longevous in terms of range at this price point. But it&#39;s possibly one of the most tech-laden and featureful if that&#39;s what you&#39;re looking for. Sometime&#39;s it feels like there&#39;s a little too much focus on the tech features and less on the ride itself. The fact that the door for feature upgrades further down the line, via the modular smart box, though, shows some welcome initiative on the company&#39;s part. For the price, though, it&#39;s an easy recommendation if you love a quantified ride and rarely go off-road.</p> This article originally appeared on Engadget at https://www.engadget.com/urtopia-chord-e-bike-151547121.html?src=rss]]>; </description><link/><![CDATA[https://www.engadget.com/urtopia-chord-e-bike-151547121.html?src=rss]]><source_id> engadget_479</source_id><guid ispermalink="false"> 76992dc8-7aef-46b5-9f48-8cc0179dd611</guid><dc:creator> James Trew</dc:creator><source/><![CDATA[Engadget]]><dc:publisher> Engadget</dc:publisher><dc:rightsholder> Engadget</dc:rightsholder><pubDate> Mon, 26 Jun 2023 15:15:47 +0000</pubDate><ingested> 1687831966</ingested><modified> 2023-06-27T02:12:51+00:00 </modified><category><![CDATA[Automotive Industry]]></category><category><![CDATA[Technology & Electronics]]></category><category><![CDATA[Cycling]]></category><category><![CDATA[site|engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[provider_name|Engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[region|US]]></category><category><![CDATA[language|en-US]]></category><category><![CDATA[author_name|James Trew]]></category><media:content height="1277" medium="image" url="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-06/2cf81480-09cf-11ee-becf-4eb07c5f1ce6" width="2000"><media:keywords> headline </media:keywords><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[1]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[ ]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[ ]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[ ]]></media:title></media:content><media:content height="1277" medium="image" url="https://media-mbst-pub-ue1.s3.amazonaws.com/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-06/2cf81480-09cf-11ee-becf-4eb07c5f1ce6" width="2000"><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[2]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[Photo by James Trew / Engadget]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[Urtopia's "Chord" e-bike is pictured on a harborside.]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[Urtopia Chord e-bike]]></media:title></media:content></item><item><title><![CDATA[Qualcomm introduces new Snapdragon 4 Gen 2 chipsets for budget-friendly phones]]></title><description type="html"><![CDATA[<p> Qualcomm <a data-i13n="cpos:1;pos:1" href="https://www.qualcomm.com/products/mobile/snapdragon/smartphones/snapdragon-4-series-mobile-platforms/snapdragon-4-gen-2-mobile-platform">just revealed its new budget-friendly mobile chipset,</a> Snapdragon 4 Gen 2. This refresh brings plenty of improvements that will kick lower-tier smartphones up a notch. The platform is designed for excellent battery life, with the company promising “all-day use.” Qualcomm also promises fast CPU speeds, 5G connectivity and the potential for upgraded visuals via integrated cameras.</p><p> The chips feature the proprietary Qualcomm Kryo CPU, with peak speeds up to 2.2 GHz, which is a <a data-i13n="cpos:2;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/qualcomm-5g-snapdragon-4-series-chipsets-073048880.html">slight increase over the previous generation.</a> Qualcomm&#39;s latest and greatest also boasts quick-charging technology, with the company stating that you get a 50 percent charge in just 15 minutes at the plug.</p><span id="end-legacy-contents"></span><p> The platform offers support for modern FHD+ displays with frame rates up to 120fps. Snapdragon 4 Gen 2 also allows for some serious camera upgrades, like electronic image stabilization, faster autofocus, enhanced blur reduction and more. The chipset even provides multi camera temporal filtering (MCTF) for drastic reduction in noise when making videos.</p><p> Of course, this is a modern product announced in the year 2023, so there&#39;s gonna be a focus on AI. This comes in the form of more camera upgrades, with AI-based lighting adjustments for snapping photos in dim environments and an AI-enhanced background noise removal tool.</p><p> As for connectivity, there&#39;s the proprietary X61 5GB Modern-RF system that promises “blazing-fast speeds” with increased network and frequency support. These chips aren&#39;t in budget-friendly smartphones yet, but they&#39;ll start showing up later in the year. OEM brands like Redmi and vivo have already pledged to begin adding the chipset to their lineups.</p> This article originally appeared on Engadget at https://www.engadget.com/qualcomm-introduces-new-snapdragon-4-gen-2-chipsets-for-budget-friendly-phones-150023133.html?src=rss]]>; </description><link/><![CDATA[https://www.engadget.com/qualcomm-introduces-new-snapdragon-4-gen-2-chipsets-for-budget-friendly-phones-150023133.html?src=rss]]><source_id> engadget_479</source_id><guid ispermalink="false"> be5f2216-0f4b-4e9f-ad01-fdcfd0a6c8cb</guid><dc:creator> Lawrence Bonk</dc:creator><source/><![CDATA[Engadget]]><dc:publisher> Engadget</dc:publisher><dc:rightsholder> Engadget</dc:rightsholder><pubDate> Mon, 26 Jun 2023 15:00:23 +0000</pubDate><ingested> 1687831967</ingested><modified> 2023-06-27T02:12:55+00:00 </modified><category><![CDATA[Technology & Electronics]]></category><category><![CDATA[site|engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[provider_name|Engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[region|US]]></category><category><![CDATA[language|en-US]]></category><category><![CDATA[author_name|Lawrence Bonk]]></category><media:content height="5304" medium="image" url="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-06/e8e969c0-11e8-11ee-ba7d-d3e0658e4a65" width="7952"><media:keywords> headline </media:keywords><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[1]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[ ]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[ ]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[ ]]></media:title></media:content><m